lished review article without citation or acknowledgment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this behaviour?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Self-plagiarism","Peer review violation","Acceptable practice in scientific writing","Data fabrication","Editorial misconduct"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes \u003Cstrong\u003Eself-plagiarism\u003C/strong\u003E, which occurs when authors reuse their own previously published work without proper citation or acknowledgment. Even when reusing one\u0027s own work, appropriate citation is required to maintain academic integrity and transparency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcceptable practice in scientific writing\u003C/strong\u003E - Reusing previously published text without citation is not acceptable academic practice\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EData fabrication\u003C/strong\u003E - This refers to making up research data or results, which is not described in this scenario\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeer review violation\u003C/strong\u003E - This involves breaching the confidentiality or integrity of the peer review process\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEditorial misconduct\u003C/strong\u003E - This relates to improper behaviour by journal editors, not authors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESelf-plagiarism can be avoided by either rewriting the content in new words or properly citing the original source. This maintains transparency about the origin of the ideas and text, allowing readers to trace the development of the work.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Research misconduct includes fabrication, falsification, and plagiarism of data or research materials.","Self-plagiarism involves reusing one\u0027s own previous work 